<dl id="n54125d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54125d">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54125d"> 125(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ as far as wind dries &amp; rain / waters turns &amp; sea bounds / give all save 7 things <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54125d"><li>FW 136.05 </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/lexfa.htm#n54125d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/l39fa.htm#n54125d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54125d">MS BL 47476a-223</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:469 <a name="fad8" href="../../ff/fdra/fda.htm#fad8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/fa/fad8.htm#n54125d">Draft: I.6&sect;1.8</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">When Kulhwch comes to ask his &ldquo;boon&rdquo; <font color="green">[family obligation]</font> of him, Arthur replies, &lsquo;Thou shalt receive the boon whatsoever thy tongue may name, <mark>as far as the wind dries, and the rain moistens, and the sun revolves, and the sea encircles, and the earth extends,&mdash;save only</mark> my ship; and my mantle; and Caledvwlch, my sword; and Rhongomyant, my lance; and Wynebgwrthucher, my shield; and Carnwennan, my dagger; and Gwenhwyvar, my wife.&rdquo; <small> W. Lewis Jones, <a name="WJKA4" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#WJKA4"><cite title="source">King Arthur in History and Legend</cite></a> (1914) 46</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
